<br>
I did some testing last night with a shm friend and a ranger.  Here were the results:<br>
<br>
DPT = damage per tick<br>
<br>
Ranger:<br>
DoT used = Niflik's (Ranger LoY spell for those not familiar)<br>
<br>
1)  CotM not on: 30 DPT<br>
<br>
2)  CotM on before DoT started:  32-34 DPT while song was on only<br>
<br>
3)  CotM on after DoT started:  30 DPT before song started, 32-34 after song started<br>
<br>
4)  CotM on before and after DoT started:  32-34 throughout duration of song<br>
<br>
Shaman:<br>
DoT used - epic (none of the other DoT's he was casting landed on the Highborn's in Veksar - so we picked a bad spot to test his DoT's)<br>
<br>
DPT did not increase on his epic DoT - believe this to be because it is not a &quot;cast&quot; spell.  This is most likely the same for all DoT's with damage assigned by items (we didn't test the ranger's arms).<br>
<br>
The testing definitely concludes that the additional DoT dmg from Call of the Muse is assigned on a per tick basis and it's not needed for it to be on at the start of a DoT to be effective.<br>
<br>
I think I could have gotten a better range of results by using necro DoT's or shm DoT's as they assign so much more damage, but unfortunately (for testing purposes) we chose to hunt in Veksar last night.<br>
<br>
